04553nam a22005775i 9780773597280DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2017381043  a97807735972807 a10.1515/97807735972802doi  a(DE-B1597)656387  a(OCoLC)904181938  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aJS78b.M235 2015 4aJS78b.M33 2015 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a320.8/52231 aMagnusson, Warren, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLocal Self-Government and the Right to the City /cWarren Magnusson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Urban Governance ;v100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Hounds that Didn't Bark -- tThe Local State in Capitalist Society -- tCommunity Organization and Local Self-Government* -- tMetropolitan Reform in the Capitalist City* -- tThe Local State in Canada: Theoretical Perspectives* -- tThirty Years On: Plus ça change … ? -- tSocial Movements and Political Space -- tGlobalization, Movements, and the Decentred State* -- tThe City as the Hope of Democracy* -- tScaling Government to Politics* -- tSeeing Like a City -- tRethinking Local Democracy -- tThe Principle of Local Self-Government* -- tAre Municipalities Creatures of the Provinces?* -- tLocal Self-Government and the Right to the City* -- tVisions of Democracy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite decades of talk about globalization, democracy still depends on local self-government. In Local Self-Government and the Right to the City, Warren Magnusson argues that it is the principle behind claims to personal autonomy, community control, and national self-determination, and holds the promise of more peaceful politics. Unfortunately, state-centred thinking has obscured understanding of what local self-government can mean and hindered efforts to make good on what activists have called the "right to the city." In this collection of essays, Magnusson reflects on his own efforts to make sense of what local self-government can actually mean, using the old ideal of the town meeting as a touchstone. Why cannot communities govern themselves? Why fear direct democracy? As he suggests, putting more trust in the proliferating practices of government and self-government will actually make cities work better, and enable us to see how to localize democracy appropriately. He shows that doing so will require citizens and governments to come to terms with the multiplicity, indeterminacy, and uncertainty implicit in politics and steer clear of sovereign solutions. The culmination of a life’s work by Canada’s leading political theorist in the field, Local Self-Government and the Right to the City ranges across topics such as local government, social movements, constitutional law, urban political economy, and democratic theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunitiesxPolitical aspects. 0aMunicipal government. 0aPolitical participation. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359728040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773597280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773597280/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles